1
00:00:06,314 --> 00:00:09,801
Welcome back to the course
on Plasma Physics and Applications.

2
00:00:10,164 --> 00:00:14,103
In the last module we have reviewed
observational data

3
00:00:14,103 --> 00:00:17,150
collected with telescopes
over two centuries,

4
00:00:17,150 --> 00:00:21,150
and recently with satellites,
that demonstrate an amazing dynamics

5
00:00:21,150 --> 00:00:23,337
of the magnetic fields in the Sun.

6
00:00:23,337 --> 00:00:25,683
We have discussed properties
of the sunspots

7
00:00:25,683 --> 00:00:28,011
where the magnetic fields
are extremely intense

8
00:00:28,260 --> 00:00:31,577
and the global structure
of the solar magnetic field,

9
00:00:31,577 --> 00:00:33,445
which reverses every 11 years.

10
00:00:33,978 --> 00:00:37,094
In the course of this lecture
I will describe how

11
00:00:37,094 --> 00:00:39,516
a magnetohydrodynamic dynamo

12
00:00:39,516 --> 00:00:42,811
which converts energy of the plasma flow
into magnetic energy

13
00:00:42,811 --> 00:00:44,783
is at the origin of these fields.

14
00:00:45,136 --> 00:00:48,434
I will use the plasma physics tools
that you have learned so far

15
00:00:48,434 --> 00:00:50,873
and I will focus
on the main physics issues

16
00:00:50,873 --> 00:00:53,265
by skipping the complicated details.

17
00:00:54,489 --> 00:00:59,377
The generation of magnetic fields
in astrophysics is an old question.

18
00:00:59,761 --> 00:01:04,563
In 1919 Larmor asked,
in a brief communication,

19
00:01:04,563 --> 00:01:06,158
the following question:

20
00:01:06,158 --> 00:01:10,552
"How could a rotating body
such as the Sun become a magnet?"

21
00:01:11,433 --> 00:01:15,063
The answer to this question
could be a dynamo process

22
00:01:15,063 --> 00:01:18,336
in which the magnetic field is generated

23
00:01:18,336 --> 00:01:20,966
by the inductive action
of a conducting fluid.

24
00:01:21,591 --> 00:01:25,625
In essence, the mechanical
energy of the flow

25
00:01:25,625 --> 00:01:28,867
can be converted into magnetic energy

26
00:01:28,867 --> 00:01:31,884
by stretching and twisting
the magnetic field lines.

27
00:01:33,065 --> 00:01:36,169
Before going into the details
of plasma physics,

28
00:01:36,169 --> 00:01:40,034
let's consider a simple mechanical dynamo

29
00:01:40,034 --> 00:01:44,407
as the one that is shown here,
called <i>homopolar disk dynamo</i>.

30
00:01:45,183 --> 00:01:50,487
Let's consider a copper disk
that rotates at an angular velocity ω.

31
00:01:51,223 --> 00:01:53,676
The rotation is externally driven,

32
00:01:53,676 --> 00:01:57,934
for example, by a motor, by applying
a torque to the axis of the disk.

33
00:01:58,410 --> 00:02:03,037
A wire which is twisted
about the axis as it is shown here

34
00:02:03,037 --> 00:02:08,464
makes a sliding contact
with the disk at points A and B.

35
00:02:10,518 --> 00:02:15,882
This wire can carry a current
that we indicate with I,

36
00:02:15,882 --> 00:02:18,292
which is a function of time, t.

37
00:02:19,823 --> 00:02:23,465
The magnetic field
associated with this current

38
00:02:23,465 --> 00:02:29,336
has a flux Φ = M I

39
00:02:29,612 --> 00:02:33,935
where M is the mutual inductance
between the wire and the disk.

40
00:02:35,483 --> 00:02:38,697
The rotation of the disk
in the presence of this magnetic flux

41
00:02:38,697 --> 00:02:41,776
generates a radial 
electromotive force [emf]

42
00:02:41,776 --> 00:02:45,317
which is equal to the angular velocity [ω]

43
00:02:45,317 --> 00:02:49,259
times the magnetic flux Φ
divided by 2π.

44
00:02:49,508 --> 00:02:52,416
This is due to the fact
that a radius of the disk

45
00:02:52,416 --> 00:02:57,652
cuts the magnetic flux Φ
once every 2π/ω seconds.

46
00:02:59,213 --> 00:03:02,415
The rotation of the copper disk
therefore results

47
00:03:02,415 --> 00:03:06,601
in a potential difference between
the axis and the edge of the disk.

48
