192
00:13:44,603 --> 00:13:48,956
This formula defines
the <i>Magnetic Reynolds Number</i>

193
00:13:48,956 --> 00:13:54,350
which is a dimensionless number,
usually indicated with Rm.

194
00:13:59,560 --> 00:14:03,641
If the Magnetic Reynolds Number
is much larger than one,

195
00:14:03,641 --> 00:14:05,187
advection dominates.

196
00:14:05,476 --> 00:14:09,699
In the opposite limit, if the Magnetic
Reynolds Number is much smaller than one,

197
00:14:09,699 --> 00:14:11,907
then diffusion dominates.

198
00:14:13,621 --> 00:14:17,662
As we will see in the following,
in astrophysical plasmas typically,

199
00:14:17,662 --> 00:14:20,771
the Magnetic Reynolds Number
is much larger than one,

200
00:14:20,771 --> 00:14:25,627
while in laboratory experiment
it is usually small,

201
00:14:25,627 --> 00:14:28,768
typically of the order of 10 or 15.

202
00:14:31,887 --> 00:14:36,581
Let's now evaluate the Magnetic
Reynolds Number for solar plasmas.

203
00:14:37,562 --> 00:14:43,253
In order to do that, we need to recall
the value of the vacuum permeability

204
00:14:43,253 --> 00:14:45,073
in SI units [4π x 10⁻⁷ Henry/m].

205
00:14:49,359 --> 00:14:53,899
To do that, we also need to recall
the expression of the plasma conductivity

206
00:14:53,899 --> 00:14:58,320
that you have derived in a previous module
which is written this way,

207
00:14:58,320 --> 00:15:04,240
and which involves the estimate of the
electron-ion collision frequency [<νei>].

208
00:15:06,212 --> 00:15:11,023
We can now recall
that the plasma conductivity

209
00:15:11,023 --> 00:15:13,667
is the inverse of the plasma resistivity,

210
00:15:13,667 --> 00:15:16,143
and for the plasma resistivity we can use

211
00:15:16,143 --> 00:15:20,602
a very useful formula
in SI units, as follows:

212
